disappointed in that attitude.

985
01:41:16,800 --> 01:41:18,279
- Fuck my ex-wives.
- I have.

986
01:41:18,400 --> 01:41:21,198
Now I know why you divorced 'em.

987
01:41:26,480 --> 01:41:33,352
Blakey! You are the only
son of a bitch who really understands me.

988
01:41:33,480 --> 01:41:36,040
- God. I love you.
- I love you, Peter.

989
01:41:36,160 --> 01:41:38,196
How sad is that?

990
01:41:41,080 --> 01:41:44,868
This script could be terrific.
We'll give it the Sellers-Edwards touch.

991
01:41:45,000 --> 01:41:48,470
- I've got lots of ideas.
- We start shooting in six weeks.

992
01:41:50,960 --> 01:41:53,030
Better make it eight.

993
01:41:54,200 --> 01:41:57,795
Peter... I'm calling the shots here.

994
01:42:28,000 --> 01:42:30,150
Darling! Over here!

995
01:42:31,840 --> 01:42:35,071
This is sure to be another
stunning success. How does it feel?

996
01:42:35,200 --> 01:42:38,112
- Well-deserved, I can assure you.
- Thank you.

997
01:42:42,080 --> 01:42:45,356
Hello, Blakey. Is this going to be
your usual load of rubbish?

998
01:42:57,640 --> 01:43:01,952
Hello, my dear friends.
Thank you for coming out tonight.

999
01:43:11,080 --> 01:43:14,436
I have something I'd like very much
to say to you all.

1000
01:43:14,560 --> 01:43:19,031
We would not all be here
if it were not for the efforts of one man -

1001
01:43:19,160 --> 01:43:24,598
one man whose vision you will soon
see writ large on the silver screen.

1002
01:43:25,560 --> 01:43:28,313
I am of course referring to Mr Blake Edwards.

1003
01:43:29,800 --> 01:43:31,472
Get him up here, folks.

1004
01:43:31,600 --> 01:43:34,398
Come on, Blakey. Up you come.

1005
01:43:35,360 --> 01:43:37,351
Jolly good.

1006
01:43:38,360 --> 01:43:41,272
- Come on!
- Thank you!

1007
01:43:42,240 --> 01:43:44,071
Thank you!

1008
01:43:46,680 --> 01:43:49,035
Let me tell you something about this man.

1009
01:43:49,160 --> 01:43:53,039
He is absolutely talentless.

1010
01:43:55,520 --> 01:43:56,157
No, but seriously, no one - and I repeat that -

1011
01:43:58,520 --> 01:44:03,310
no one has managed to do so much,
having so very little.

1012
01:44:05,200 --> 01:44:06,428
Give me that.

1013
01:44:06,560 --> 01:44:09,233
People ask me
why I compromise my artistic integrity

1014
01:44:09,360 --> 01:44:11,590
by walking in front of Blake's cameras.

1015
01:44:13,480 --> 01:44:16,677
You know what I tell them? Money.

1016
01:44:17,520 --> 01:44:19,590
It's true.

1017
01:44:22,400 --> 01:44:25,437
That and the knowledge that
no matter how bad the picture is,

1018
01:44:25,560 --> 01:44:27,790
I'll always be the best thing in it.

1019
01:44:28,720 --> 01:44:31,917
- Thank you.
- Oh, look, he's bashful, folks.

1020
01:44:32,600 --> 01:44:36,673
Why shouldn't he be?
In an industry that worships mediocrity,

1021
01:44:36,800 --> 01:44:39,712
you, Blake, truly have added new lustre

1022
01:44:39,840 --> 01:44:43,037
to the term "middling talent".

1023
01:44:47,600 --> 01:44:51,593
So enjoy the show... if that's at all possible.

1024
01:45:02,920 --> 01:45:04,831
I...

1025
01:45:07,080 --> 01:45:09,116
I knew we should've gotten Ustinov.

1026
01:45:50,680 --> 01:45:54,798
<i>The ambitious Sellers</i>
<i>presents a portrait of determination</i>.

1027
01:45:57,840 --> 01:46:00,354
<i>You've reached the home of Peter Sellers</i>.

1028
01:46:00,440 --> 01:46:05,036
<i>Mr Sellers is unable to take your call,</i>
<i>as he is off leading a normal life</i>.

1029
01:46:05,160 --> 01:46:07,913
<i>Please leave your message</i>
<i>after the series of tones</i>.

1030
01:46:09,080 --> 01:46:11,275
<i>Oh. Hi, Dad, it's me, Mike</i>.

1031
01:46:11,400 --> 01:46:15,439
<i>I tried you on the phone but Sarah</i>
<i>thought you might be in Switzerland</i>.

1032
01:46:15,560 --> 01:46:19,872
<i>Anyway, Mum told me about the operation,</i>
<i>the pacemaker and everything</i>.

1033
01:46:20,000 --> 01:46:23,151
<i>That must be fun</i>.
<i>I know how you like gadgets</i>.

1034
01:46:24,520 --> 01:46:27,557
<i>Well, anyway, I hope you're, er, you're OK</i>.

1035
01:46:28,480 --> 01:46:31,278
<i>Right, take care, Dad. Bye</i>.

1036
01:46:54,120 --> 01:46:56,759
I'm just an old, salty sea dog.

1037
01:47:30,840 --> 01:47:33,195
Peter, are you in there?

1038
01:47:36,480 --> 01:47:38,994
Will you give me a goddamn break already?

1039
01:47:45,200 --> 01:47:49,398
You know something, Sellers,
you are a major league pain in the ass.

1040
01:47:50,360 --> 01:47:52,271
Peter!

1041
01:48:02,720 --> 01:48:06,793
Was he difficult? He was the star -
of course he was difficult.

1042
01:48:07,600 --> 01:48:10,478
You know who's not difficult? Troy Donahue.

1043
01:48:12,240 --> 01:48:15,038
Christ. I need a smoke.

1044
01:48:17,840 --> 01:48:21,150
I worked with Sellers for what,
20 years, on and off?

1045
01:48:25,640 --> 01:48:28,154
Six movies.

1046
01:48:28,280 --> 01:48:30,475
I never laughed so hard.

1047
01:48:31,320 --> 01:48:33,390
I never cried so hard.

1048
01:48:36,080 --> 01:48:39,436
The last straw?
There were endless last straws.

1049
01:48:39,560 --> 01:48:43,439
You say, "last straw",
five seconds later you're saying, "Action".

1050
01:48:43,560 --> 01:48:47,951
I can't explain it. It was like watching a cobra.

1051
01:48:49,760 --> 01:48:51,671
You're mesmerised.

1052
01:48:54,520 --> 01:48:56,670
What did he do after me?

1053
01:49:00,480 --> 01:49:02,914
The only thing he never gave up on.

1054
01:49:06,840 --> 01:49:09,274
They all wanted me to be a clown.

1055
01:49:09,400 --> 01:49:14,110
They'll pay me millions to be a French,
mustachioed, karate-chopping twit.

1056
01:49:15,240 --> 01:49:17,834
But this is so much more.

1057
01:49:17,960 --> 01:49:20,315
What do you want to do, Peter?

1058
01:49:24,640 --> 01:49:26,835
Isn't that what I just asked you?

1059
01:50:45,040 --> 01:50:46,917
Oh, shut up.

1060
01:52:17,120 --> 01:52:18,439
Yowser.

1061
01:52:19,680 --> 01:52:22,399
Ain't you the gentleman this mornin'?

1062
01:52:25,560 --> 01:52:27,551
I'm gonna go now.

1063
01:52:28,160 --> 01:52:30,071
Yes.

1064
01:52:31,440 --> 01:52:33,556
You're gonna need somebody.

1065
01:52:35,040 --> 01:52:39,033
You oughta find yourself a lady, Chance.

1066
01:52:40,040 --> 01:52:42,634
Guess it oughta be an old lady,

1067
01:52:42,760 --> 01:52:46,753
cos you ain't gonna
do a young one any good.

1068
01:52:46,880 --> 01:52:49,872
Not with that little thing of yours.

1069
01:52:52,720 --> 01:52:55,632
You're always gonna be a little boy, ain't you?

1070
01:53:04,040 --> 01:53:05,951
Bye, Chance.

1071
01:53:17,200 --> 01:53:19,111
Bye, Louise.

1072
01:53:34,560 --> 01:53:38,519
'Scuse me. 'Scuse me.
Aren't you Peter Sellers?

1073
01:53:40,440 --> 01:53:43,830
- Yes, I am.
- Would you mind?

1074
01:53:51,680 --> 01:53:56,754
Thank you. Thank you very much. I mean,
you... you were... the man. That's it.

1075
01:54:47,120 --> 01:54:49,953
<i>You're always gonna be a little boy,</i>
<i>ain't you?</i>

1076
01:54:51,920 --> 01:54:53,751
<i>Bye, Chance</i>.

1077
01:54:55,400 --> 01:54:57,311
<i>Bye, Louise</i>.

1078
01:56:37,760 --> 01:56:41,070
Mr Edwards.
Pardon me, but have you seen Mr Sellers?

1079
01:56:41,200 --> 01:56:43,395
No, and he's 20 minutes late. Did he call?

1080
01:56:43,520 --> 01:56:45,431
No. He's here.

1081
01:56:45,560 --> 01:56:47,755
I think maybe you should see him.

1082
01:57:17,640 --> 01:57:19,392
Peter?

1083
01:59:22,960 --> 01:59:24,871
You can't come in here.

